The fossilised remains of "Diploria strigosa" have been found alongside those of other massive corals, "Diploria clivosa", "Siderastrea siderea" and "Solenastrea bouroni", in marine deposits in Río Grande de Manatí, Puerto Rico that date back to the Pleistocene.
Dickinson studied chemistry and physics at Harvard University with a bachelor's degree completed in 1961. As a graduate student, he studied meteorology at Massachusetts Institute of Technology (MIT) with a master's degree in 1962 and Ph.D. in 1966. After being a researcher at MIT, he joined in 1968 the National Center for Atmospheric Research (NCAR) in Boulder, Colorado, where he became in 1975 head of the climate division and in 1981 Deputy Director of the Climate and Global Dynamics Division. In 1990 he became a professor at the University of Arizona, in 1999 professor at Georgia Institute of Technology (GT), and since 2008 professor at the University of Texas at Austin (UT).

